# Building a Custom Visualization

Here we have a bar chart of four years of data (artificial dataset). Each year has a y-axis value, which is derived from a sample of a larger dataset. For instance, the first value might be the number votes in a given district or riding for 1992, with the average being around 33,000. On top of this is plotted the 95% confidence interval for the mean.

The challenge is to allow users set a range of y values (e.g. 35,000 to 42,000) they are interested in, and recolor based on this  and then draw a horizontal line and color bars based on this value (given the confidence interval).


```python
%matplotlib notebook
import pandas as pd
import numpy as np
import matplotlib as mpl
import matplotlib.pyplot as plt
import math
from scipy import stats
from scipy.stats import norm
from scipy.stats import ttest_1samp
import matplotlib.gridspec as gridspec

'''
Function to adjust position in the y axis of graph
'''

def position_yaxis(axs, 
                   howmuch, 
                   bot = None):
    h = None
    if bot == True:
        h = 3
    else: 
        h = 1
    exit_lst = [k for k in axs.get_position().bounds]
    exit_lst[h] = exit_lst[h] - howmuch
    return exit_lst

'''
Interactivity. You can click on the bar chart and move the mouse 
to another value and to set the range. First we have the click event 
on the graph
'''

def onclick(event):     
    global y1 # we set the variable y1 as global to use it in the fill  between lines
    y1 = event.ydata
    
    principal.axhline(y1, 
                      color='gray', 
                      alpha=0.5, 
                      lw=0.5)
    
    principal.text(1991.45, 
                   y1-2000, 
                   '{0:.2f}'.format(y1))
    
    d1 = plt.gcf().canvas.mpl_connect('button_release_event', 
                                      releaseclick)
'''
Second we have the event of releasing the click.
'''
    
def releaseclick(event): 
    principal.cla() 
    
    '''
    We create/update the lines when we release the 
    click and fill between them.
    '''
    
    principal.axhline(event.ydata, 
                      color='gray', 
                      alpha=0.5, 
                      lw=0.5)
    
    principal.text(1991.45, 
                   event.ydata+500, 
                   '{0:.2f}'.format(event.ydata))
    
    principal.axhline(y1, 
                      color='gray', 
                      alpha=0.5, 
                      lw=0.5)
    
    principal.text(1991.45, 
                   y1-2000, 
                   '{0:.2f}'.format(y1))
    
    principal.axhspan(event.ydata, 
                      y1, 
                      color='gray', 
                      alpha=0.25)
    
    
    
    '''
    We set the colors of the bars based on the error bars
    '''
    cm = []
    
    for i in range(1992,1996):
        _ , pval_sup = ttest_1samp(df.T[i], event.ydata)
        _ , pval_inf = ttest_1samp(df.T[i], y1)
        pval = np.abs(pval_inf - pval_sup)
        cm.append(
            [
                v for k,v in df_colors.items() 
                if pval > float(k[0]) and pval < float(k[1])
            ][0]
        )
        
    '''
    Update chart
    '''
    principal.bar(df.index,
                  df.mean(axis=1),
                  width=0.8,
                  tick_label=[k for k in range(1992, 1996)],
                  edgecolor='black',
                  yerr=df.sem(axis = 1)*norm.ppf(0.975),
                  capsize=10,
                  align='center',
                  color=cm)
    
    principal.set_title('Mean value Over a Dataset', 
                        fontsize=15, 
                        weight='bold')
    
    fig.canvas.mpl_disconnect(d1)             

'''
We create an artificial dataset
'''

np.random.seed(12345)

df = pd.DataFrame([np.random.normal(32000,200000,3650), 
                   np.random.normal(43000,100000,3650), 
                   np.random.normal(43500,140000,3650), 
                   np.random.normal(48000,70000,3650)], 
                   index=[1992,1993,1994,1995])

'''
Colors for the charts
'''

df_colors = dict(
    zip(
        [
            (
                '{0:.2f}'.format(x*1/9), '{0:.2f}'.format(1/9 + 1/9*x)
            ) for x in range(0, 9)
        ], 
        [
            mpl.colors.rgb2hex(mpl.cm.get_cmap('Pastel1') (i)) 
            for i in range(mpl.cm.get_cmap('Pastel1').N)
        ]
    )
)


'''
Create figure and "colorbar"
'''

gspec = gridspec.GridSpec(9, 1)

principal = plt.subplot(gspec[0:-1, 0:])
color_b = plt.subplot(gspec[-1:, 0:])

'''
Set initial conditions
'''

principal.set_title('Mean value Over a Dataset', 
                    fontsize=15, 
                    weight='bold',  
                    fontname='fantasy')

principal.bar(df.index,
              df.mean(axis=1),
              width=0.8,
              tick_label=[k for k in range(1992, 1996)],
              edgecolor = 'black',
              yerr=df.sem(axis = 1) * norm.ppf(0.975),
              capsize=10,
              align='center')

'''
We create the "colorbar"
'''

col_map = plt.get_cmap('Pastel1')

cbar = mpl.colorbar.ColorbarBase(color_b,
                                 cmap=col_map,
                                 orientation='horizontal',
                                 ticks=[float('{0:.2f}'.format(x*1/9)) for x in range(0, 10)])

color_b.set_position(position_yaxis(color_b, 0.01))
color_b.set_position(position_yaxis(color_b, 0.05, bot=True))

'''
Set style to improve rendering
'''

mpl.style.use(['seaborn-pastel', 'seaborn-ticks'])

'''
Connect the interactivity
'''

plt.gcf().canvas.mpl_connect('button_press_event', onclick)

plt.show();
```
